Collapse of the Soviet Union eventually made all states in East Europe to become democratic. Democracy now has a prominent presence in Eastern Europe, yet marked differences continue to exist with countries that suffered the least from the totalitarian regimes. And more significantly, the betrayal of democratic ideals has proved to be influenced by those attempts to “catch up” with the Western xenophobes. The authors make a lot of achievements that these countries have enjoyed, and similarities to their freedoms and increasing human substantive being addressed. Several factors prevent Lithuania and the other electrified states to become democratic states: i.) the predominance of economic issues, ii.) the loosening of Communist ideology, iii.) the growing populism, iv.) the indignation against the ruling elite groups. All of these outcomes, underemployed and danger of political instability that can beget either a unilateral decision making approach that can be used to resist the opposition of other countries. Despite the problematic situation and strong efforts of the Lithuanian government to promote democracy in the country, the results are poor. The authors believe the best way to implement democracy in Lithuania is to use the appropriate governance practices. That is the model.
